@node Pank "<POLISH ACCENT> Structured programming is no good </POLISH ACCENT>"

        @{b}What's wrong with structured programming@{ub}

For decades student programmers are taught to avoid 'spagetti code'
by structured programming.

Well, that's the biggest mistake ever!!!

The disadvantages of structured programming

- The coder puts too much attention into structuring procedures, rather than
  spending the time making the code work!

- A 'structured programmer' tends to lose the total overview; concentrating
  only on one procedure at the time.
  Making a program 'as a whole' is important; a chain is just as strong
  as the weakest link!

- 'Structured programs' tend to be bloated in size. Don't ask me why,
  it just seems like it in practice. And bloated code has very nasty
  disadvantages:

  - More lines of code = more potential bugs
  - More instructions for the same result = more execution time = sluggish
    performance



The advantage(?) of structured programming

- Less time wasted on "GOTO's"

Wait a minute... Duh... Those modern CPU's have those nifty things
like superscalar execution and branch prediction, right?!?

Meaning that "GOTO's" are 'timeless'. With the '060 as example:
You can have a "GOTO" instruction every 2 other instructions
without slowing the CPU down!!!

Whoops!!! there went the only advantage of structured programming!

And suddenly the book "GOTOs considered harmful" is only useful to light
the fireplace!

The quiche eater is DEAD! Welcome back the RealProgrammer!!!
@endnode
